// Template for the deployable Callout (fsm) Worker — a SANDBOX-CLEAN, control-plane-less
// vertical (docs/design/scope-local-permissions.md, Phase 3).
//
// `wrangler.jsonc` itself is gitignored — it holds your account-specific D1
// database_id once you create one. Set up your local copy with:
//
//   cp wrangler.example.jsonc wrangler.jsonc
//
// `wrangler dev` then works as-is (local D1, no Cloudflare account). To DEPLOY, this
// vertical is PUSHED into the Workers-for-Platforms dispatch namespace, not deployed
// with `wrangler deploy`:
//
//   wrangler d1 create substrat-fsm-auth        # prints a database_id
//   # paste that id into AUTH_DB's "database_id" below (replacing "local")
//   wrangler d1 migrations apply substrat-fsm-auth --remote
//   substrat login                                    # stores the control plane URL + SERVICE_TOKEN
//   substrat push demos/callout --slug callout --version <v>
//   # then admit + promote the version in the console; a scope binds it via the dashboard
//
// SANDBOX CONTRACT (self-serve-deploy.md §4). This worker's ONLY bindings are its OWN
// stores: its SCOPE DO class and its AUTH_DB (a D1 it created). NO CONTROL_PLANE binding,
// no service binding to a platform worker — the deploy endpoint refuses those. It has no
// control plane at all: permissions evaluate from each scope's own storage, and the
// router asserts the (tenant, scope) node in signed headers.
//
// BEHIND THE ROUTER (K-26). This worker does not assume it serves one fixed tenant. The
// router resolves hostname → (tenant, scope, surface) and asserts it in `x-substrat-*`
// headers; this worker reads them via `readRoutedNode`. That makes two facts load-bearing:
//
//   1. NO PUBLIC ROUTE. `workers.dev` is OFF and there is no route — the router reaches
//      this worker through the dispatch namespace. If it were publicly reachable, anyone
//      could name a tenant in a header.
//   2. `wrangler secret put ROUTER_SECRET`, the SAME value as the router's — what keeps
//      (1) from being the only thing between a config slip and a cross-tenant read.
//
// PROVISIONING (K-31). `wrangler secret put PLATFORM_SECRET`, matching the control plane's.
// The control plane calls POST /internal/provision to create an instance here, because
// only this deployment can create a scope DO carrying the modules. Unset ⇒ provisioning is
// REFUSED — an unconfigured copy of this template must not provision for strangers.
//
// For local `wrangler dev` (no router) set ALLOW_DEV_HEADER=true — it both trusts the
// `x-principal` header and falls back to a fixed dev node. `pnpm cf:dev` sets it via --var
// rather than in `vars` below, ON PURPOSE: in `vars` it would ride into a real deploy,
// where an unrouted request would quietly serve a dev tenant instead of failing.
{
  "name": "substrat-fsm",
  "main": "src/worker.ts",
  "compatibility_date": "2025-01-01",
  // Not reachable except through the router once deployed. See (1) above.
  "workers_dev": false,
  // Better Auth (edge authentication, M3) needs Node built-ins on workerd.
  "compatibility_flags": ["nodejs_compat"],
  // Build the SPA and inline it into the worker BEFORE bundling. Wrangler runs this on
  // every `wrangler dev` / `deploy` / `--dry-run` — including the `--dry-run` a
  // `substrat push` performs — so a push always ships the current UI. A pushed vertical
  // has no ASSETS binding (WfP static assets are a separate upload path); the built SPA
  // rides along as ordinary worker modules instead (src/assets.ts + scripts/gen-assets.mjs).
  "build": {
    "command": "pnpm --dir app build && node scripts/gen-assets.mjs"
  },
  "durable_objects": {
    "bindings": [{ "name": "SCOPE", "class_name": "ScopeDO" }]
  },
  // Better Auth's own store (identity, credentials, sessions), and the CP-less identity
  // binding `user.principal_id` (migrations/0002). Separate from the scope DOs. "local"
  // works under wrangler dev; replace it with your real D1 database_id to deploy.
  "d1_databases": [
    { "binding": "AUTH_DB", "database_name": "substrat-fsm-auth", "database_id": "local" }
  ],
  "migrations": [
    {
      "tag": "v1",
      "new_sqlite_classes": ["ScopeDO"]
    }
  ]
}
